Results.Title: I love cycling!
Results.ReviewText: I rode on an old (vintage) Trek borrowed from a friend for about five months (including one triathlon) before realizing I loved cycling and needed to invest myself. This was the perfect bike for me. I knew I wanted a Endurance after I fell in love with the sport even on a 25 year old ride. I planned on getting the entry level Endurance but after research and discussion with my pro shop, I felt like a bit of an upgrade would be a better long term fit for me. I am so happy I made that decision. I am addicting to cycling with my new bike, I go as much as I can. The gear shifting is extremely smooth, the bike is light, and the ride is very smooth. I absolutely love it. Even after having only cycled since June, I'm Endurance loyal. I'm training for more triathlons in the spring and then my first IronMan 70.3 in September! Thank you, Endurance, I love my bike! I would ABSOLUTELY recommend this bike for a beginner who doesn't want to outgrow a entry level soon up to a seasoned rider. Fantastic bike!

Results.Title: This bike is a steal
Results.ReviewText: 500 Mile review. Local bike store agreed this bike was a steal at under $600. My husband ordered the Storm 2 and he said the same about it. The bike rides well, really well. The fork does a nice job of reducing road chatter and the Shimano 105 group set is smooth. I wouldn't say this bike kills hills, but they also don't stand in its way. The double chain ring serves its purpose, and from what I've read a triple wouldn't be any huge benefit unless you're really climbing. I swapped pedals from the provided wellgo to Shimano M530 SPD. I've found the seat adequate with no neat to change for now. All in all, I couldn't be more satisfied.

Results.Title: Way better
Results.ReviewText: Before purchasing my Endurance Apex 2, I was riding an Electra Townie. I love my Townie dearly but after doing a Gran Fondo (60 miles) on it, I realized I REALLY needed to upgrade to a road bike. Since this was a large purchase for me, I was very diligent in my research. I wanted a bike that was entry-level enough for a beginner but something that would last me for several years; basically I didn't want to out grow my new bike as quickly as I had my Townie. After months of exhausting research I settled on the Apex 2 and I have to say - I could not be more pleased! I've had it just under a month and I've logged about 200 miles. I can't believe how smooth it rides, how lightweight, and how easy it handles. Overall, it's fantastic!! I'm already planning my next Gran Fondo in September!

Results.Title: First road bike
Results.ReviewText: For the most part, I absolutely love my Apex 2. This is my first road bike, and I have transitioned from mountain biking to regular training with no significant problems on this bike. It is very lightweight, and the overall geometry and fit is great. I replaced the seat with a split-nose model for comfort, and now I find I have no problem taking the bike on 4+ hour rides. My one complaint is that the braking/shifting levers are very poorly positioned for small hands. I am 5' 2" and purchased a 47 frame, but the brakes are one size fits all. I am not able to brake from the hoods, even with the largest inserts available to push the handles towards me. Even trying to keep my hands stretched to a "ready" position for braking gives me hand pain for a few days after a long ride. I would recommend trying this out in-store if you have smaller hands; otherwise, really awesome, reliable bike.

Results.Title: Ex mountain biker loves this bike
Results.ReviewText: This is my first road bike, having been on a mountain bike or running for 25 years. I'm not getting a lot of road time as it's very winter here in the northeast. But my time on the trainer has been quite comfortable right from the start. It has been designed to specifically fit a woman, but the first thing we had to do was switch out the stem to a longer one to accommodate my longer upper body. However the Decoupler is a noticeable feature adding to the smooth ride. Other than that I am very pleased with my new Endurance!

Results.Title: Smooth operator
Results.ReviewText: I purchased this bike about three weeks ago. It is my second road bike. The first was the Challenger model. This bike is definately a smooth operator. I could not tell that I was shifting it was so smooth and quiet. It handles like a dream. Like many other Endurance bikes I have tested, this one is perfectly made to fit me. When I got fitted on it, the bike shop showed me the coolest feature. The ability to move the brake levers closer to me so I do not have to be stuck in one hand position in the drops. The Endurance Apex 2 is definately the perfect bike for me!

Results.Title: So light
Results.ReviewText: I am retired and like to ride on paved bike paths for 10 to 30 miles several times a week. Compared to my Trek Hybrid, the Apex 2 is so light, about 20% lighter as configured. Smooth shifting and very fast. The seat could be more comfortable as after a two hour or longer ride you wish it were. I did have one minor problem with the bike after about 300 miles, the rear brake cable let loose. No biggie, just reattached and tightened.

Results.Title: Great package
Results.ReviewText: The Apex 2 is genuinely a great package especially for a woman of my shape and size. Sure you can find higher componentry packages online but imho you can't beat the handling of the Enduranceframes and what you get with the 2 is all the r&d that goes into the higher end models filtered down for under a grand. Its light, comfy (apart from a saddle change but I'm very picky on that front) and beautiful to ride for the money. I would highly recommend it to anyone looking for their first race bike, a fast training bike or a good all round enthusiasts steed.

Results.Title: Love the Apex 2
Results.ReviewText: I ended up getting the Apex 2 from a local dealer since they were the only one who had my size. I absolutely love this bike. It is comfortable, fast and you can actually tell how aerodynamic it is. I just completed my first half century and if I was riding with people as soon as I went to the lower bar on the hills I would immediately pull away from people without even trying. My top speed on the decents was 49.2 mph vs my riding partners being 45 and 42. It rides great and is simply a great bike all round. For the price you really can't beat it. And it really does look sharp. My husband can hardly keep up. :)

Results.Title: Great bike for summer
Results.ReviewText: In my opinion, ths is by far the best bike out there for <$1,000. I bought exact same bike online last summer for $150 more and I absolutely love it...had to buy another after I failed to secure the last one properly on my Thule :( It rides like a dream, its very smooth and its not very stiff for a aluminum bike. The geometry of the Apex 2 is set-up more for a long distance rider, you are definitely stretched over the top-tube of the bike. This is the position that I ride in the most. If you are looking for a fast, very lightweight, very affordable, long distance bike...this is the one. I enjoyed this bike so much, that I bought a Endurance Pace for my oldest son. That bike has a very different frame geometry. Its a bike that thats made for people who will be standing on the pedals often.

Results.Title: Light and String
Results.ReviewText: I didn't know if the (fairly) reasonable price meant that the quality would suffer, but it doesn't. This is a great bike. Very light, strong and with a little know how (or a friendly bike shop repair man) can be assembled in a couple of hours. I've upgraded the crank set to a Shimano Ultegra and may do the same for a few other little bits to treak it, but I highly recommend this cool looking machine. Buy it, buy it, buy it...
